This morning our little podcast @yassjesuspod was nominated for a @Glaad media award. Both @religioustrade and I are conversion therapy survivors and this is so affirming to know that we have created a queer safe space for folks looking for a place to wonder, worship, question authority, find a sense of community and reconcile with their faith. We started in my living room and now are well into the third season after traveling to Jerusalem now London and all around the USA letting everyone know you don't have to choose between gay and God. We have worked so hard and  spend so much money and sacrificed many a Sunday to record. After separating from our producing entity and having to buy all new equipment and keep the shoes running despite our crazy schedules and demands of our lives. We are SO grateful to our listeners who have shared their stories with us and donated money and sent in praise reports and prayer requests. Our dynamic guests and amazing team our tireless editor Chris Heckman our producers @la.bete.noire (who has produced us from a laptop on sets that many would deem an impossible feat) and The freakin Deacon @inlayterms who while traveling the world on great missions always managed to have a great plan for each episode. stay tuned for prayers from you favorite drag queens @therajaoharashow @thedannybeard @heidincloset @bluhydrangea_  @angeriavm @scarletenvy @bagachipz and MORE!

En route to our nations capital to represent @elizabethtayloraidsfoundation for the 6th time at #AIDSWATCH to take in person capitol visits to lobby our Congress to remind them that #HIVisNOTaCRIME asking to rethink and remove antiquated criminal laws and penalty enhancements that still exist in 35 states, that effect people living with HIV. I'm proud to carry on Ms Taylor's and her family's tireless efforts to draw attention and care to our Lgbtq siblings and allies who need it. We as LGBTQ folks have so much on the line with HIV Stigma, youth homelessness, conversion therapy, even now even drag is at risk. For years they have used old fear based laws like these against us to fire us or kick us out of our homes or incarcerated us. I'm HIV negative and I am on PrEp and continue to monitor my sexual health status. I urge all of you to get get tested , Get PrEP ( a really easy way could be through @getqcareplus if anyone has seen our commercial during @rupaulsdragrace ) We need to stand up and be vocal and take care of our community. We are a community AND a movement. One thing this fight always reminds me is how many of our elders we have lost. We need to fight double as hard for them. Please VOTE. 📷 by @seanblackofficial

NEW ISSUE ALERT 🚨 From the big screen to stand-up to drag, Daniel Franzese had been entertaining audiences through laughter and vulnerability. 

Currently, his focus is on spreading faith as a Christian through his podcast, Yass, Jesus! Dealing with the struggle of religion versus faith, he brought himself into conversion therapy. Whereas many members of the LGBTQ community have walked away from their faith, Daniel has forged his own path and he’s not afraid to spread the word.

“I had a promise to God. I always said to God that if I could just be in the closet and be an actor when I finally came out, my platform would be that God loves gay people too. But that’s not how it happened.”

Read the full interview at gedmag.com

Last night's @hairsprayontour was a theater experience I will never forget. @ninawest and an inspired cast made the audience(which was full of the most talented LGBTQ people in Hollywood) lose our minds with laughter, let our eyes well up with tears and marvel at Nina skillful voice, lighter than air dancing and huge heart. The mob was buzzing at the after party DO NOT MISS this production. If you ever wanted to see #HAIRSPRAY now if the time. I'm a huge John Waters fan but the OG movie was not only hilarious but was the first to help me as a kid understand what life was like in the 60s for Black folks on TV. The revolutionary themes of race and even DRAG hit home harder than ever. Segregation NEVER! Integration NOW! #supportlivetheatre #ninawestisastar #equalityforall

If you want to get all the gory and emotional details of my ordeal listen to this Sundays episode of @yassjesuspod It was important as a person who shows most of my life on social media to be transparent. We lack discussion around gay mens sexual health/health. Unless we are getting yelled at by the CDC about monkey pox , AIDS, poppers... we don't ever get clinical studies or have public discussions about health. So what, it's a little embarrassing or maybe an over share but it could save lives. I cannot believe I almost lost my own over using a TikTok home remedy. Thank you all again for your continued love and support. I really feel it. ❤️‍🩹

I'm not doing the surgery yet but DrRome and the team think I would benefit from a treatment of pills, a proprietary topical solution and a few shots. I am excited about this new journey. Meditating on the serenity prayer this is how to take action on some of the things I can change. It's also in both weho and soho so I know where to get the proper care here and in NYC. its exciting and a little nervy anticipating the results but will keep everyone updated as part of holding myself accountable for all these new changes and self care. Featured Panelist: DANIEL FRANZESE

Actor, Advocate, Podcast Host

Daniel Franzese is a multi-talented American actor, comedian, and writer. He rose to fame with his roles in the popular movies "Mean Girls" and "Bully", and has also appeared in the TV series "Looking". Apart from his acting career, Daniel is also an active member of the Elizabeth Taylor AIDS Foundation, promoting awareness about HIV/AIDS. He has used his platform to advocate for LGBTQ rights and body positivity. Furthermore, he has a successful faith-based podcast called "Yass, Jesus!" that has gained a lot of attention. Marboro Theatre. Brooklyn,NY. 1927-2007 

I saw my first movie here BAMBI (as on the marquee) I also remember seeing Goonies, Annie and The Neverending Story here and thinking I wanted to be an actor so bad.  I went back here when it was a church in its last days and soaked up the memory for a bit. When any theatre or cinema palace closes I mourn it a little bit. Painting this today made me think about how much it inspired me and how the fantasy seemed so accessible on that screen. I have only seen this building a bit rundown and never without graffiti ( it was the 80s after all) It was torn down for a CVS in 2007 but it stands majestically clean and tall in my memory. What was your first movie?
